      h1 Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve
      p The protection of wildlife, especially of birds and forests in Letea and Caraorman levees, of the  typical landscapes of the delta, was established even before the Second World War, due to the ever more intrusive presence of  man in the Danube Delta. Thanks to the Romanian naturalists perseverance, the Natural Park Letea was set up in 1930 and Roşca-Buhaiova Reserve in 1940, listed in the year 1970 in the world list of biosphere reserves among other 177 reserves, part of Man and Biosphere UNESCO Program (MAB). 
      p After 1950, due to the reorganization of the Commission of Natural Monuments of the Romanian Academy (founded in 1930 by Law no. 213) the number of reserves in the delta area has been increased to five reserves (three ornithological and two forests reserves) summarize approximately 40,000 hectares of protected areas, adding also breeding sites of less protective regime. 
      p
        | The fundamental changes that took place in the Romanian society, after 1989, have lead to the value reevaluation of the Danube Delta, the scientific interest for protecting this area was prioritary over  the economic interest. Thus, by 
        strong Government Decision no. 983/ 27 August 1990 (Art. 5), Danube Delta together with Razim-Sinoe lacustrian complex, Sărături - Murighiol lake, Isaccea – Tulcea lacustrian complex (the natural Danube floodplain between Isaccea and Tulcea), the riverbed of the Danube between Cotul Pisicii and Ceatalul Chiliei, also the costal sea waters until the 20 meters depth line
        |, were declared a biosphere reserve. This decision was followed by the development and approval in the Romanian Parliament of the Law no.82/1993 where the structure of the reserve is established, along with the administration of the area and the ecological reconstruction of damaged areas. 
      p
        | According to the concept of a Biosphere Reserve, man and his activity shouldn’t be excluded, but integrated in the protected area, so that the economic activity can cohabit with the conservation and protection. The international value of the Danube Delta was recognized and included in the world wide network of Biosphere Reserves in the year 1990, within the “Man and Biosphere“ program launched by UNESCO in  1970.  Also, the Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve was recognized as 
        em wetland of international importance, especially as waterfowl habitat
        |, according to the Ramsar Convention, signed by Romania in 1991. Considering the universal heritage value of the Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve, it was included in the 
        em List of World Cultural and Natural Heritage 
        |in 1990. 
      p
        | According to Law No. 82/1993 and the Government decision no. 248/1994, the Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve, with all its physical-geographical units presented above, has a total area of 580,000 ha. Within these limits, the reserve is structured into 20 
        strong Strictly Protected Areas
        |, covering 50,904 ha, buffer areas with a total area of 222,996 ha, and 
        strong sustainable development areas
        |, including villages/towns and 
        strong ecological restoration sites
        |, with a total area of 306,100 ha.
